  "response_text": "The commercial opens in black and white with a large Northwest airliner flying through thick, bright clouds. The airplane is seen mostly from the side, nose pointing left and tail to the right. It has a long, smooth fuselage lined with small passenger windows, four propeller engines mounted under the wings, and a tall tail fin with airline markings. The propellers appear as blurred discs, suggesting motion. For several moments the aircraft remains the central image, cruising steadily among billowing clouds that fill the background and drift around the wings and tail.\n\nThe image changes to a graphic title over an airplane silhouette: large bold capital letters read “NORTHWEST,” with “Orient” written below in a flowing script style, and “AIRLINES” in smaller block capitals to the right. The plane appears behind or beneath the lettering, reinforcing the airline identity.\n\nA brief scene follows in a Japanese-style interior. A young woman, presented in traditional dress, sits on the floor near a large rectangular paper-paneled screen. She wears a light-colored kimono with wide sleeves and has a formal, rounded hairstyle. She holds a long-necked stringed instrument across her lap, resembling a shamisen, with one hand near the body of the instrument and the other along the neck. Her posture is composed and upright, and she looks gently toward the viewer with a slight smile. The setting is simple and uncluttered, with pale walls and the grid pattern of the screen behind her.\n\nThe commercial returns to the airplane imagery. A close side view of the nose and forward engines of a propeller airliner fills the background while large white text appears over it. The words “shortest...” and “fastest” are clearly visible in stacked lowercase letters, with “route” partly visible beneath, and the word “Orient” written large in cursive across the lower part of the picture. The plane’s cockpit windows, front passenger windows, and spinning propellers are visible behind the lettering.\n\nA map graphic then appears, shaped like a globe with the northern Pacific region visible. Pale landmasses and ocean areas are shown in a simplified style. A dark route line stretches across the map from the Seattle area toward destinations in Asia, with labels including “SEATTLE,” “TOKYO,” and “MANILA” visible near the left side. A small airplane silhouette sits on or near the route line, showing the path of travel. The line includes angled segments, visually emphasizing a shortcut route across the Pacific.\n\nThe map gradually gives way to another view of the Northwest airliner in flight. The plane now appears above a landscape partly hidden by scattered clouds. The aircraft is again seen from above and to the side, its long fuselage crossing diagonally through the scene, with four propeller engines and a marked tail fin. Below, faint shapes of land, fields, roads, or coastlines are visible through breaks in the clouds. The airliner continues smoothly through open sky, surrounded by puffy cloud banks.\n\nNear the end, the imagery shifts to an Asian-inspired decorative setting. A large round gong hangs in front of a dark background of vertical bamboo-like poles or curtains. A hand and forearm, wearing a patterned sleeve, reach in from the left holding a padded mallet. The mallet touches or strikes the center area of the gong, then appears again against the metallic surface. The gong is bright and textured, reflecting light across its circular face.\n\nOver the gong, the airline title returns in bold white lettering: “NORTHWEST” dominates the center in large capital letters, with “Orient” beneath it in cursive script and “AIRLINES” in block capitals to the right. The hand with the mallet remains partly visible at the left edge at first, then the final image settles on the glowing round gong behind the prominent “NORTHWEST Orient AIRLINES” name.",
